3.1.3. Queue Logic and Strategy
a. Flow Control Mechanism
The system employs an in-memory buffering strategy to regulate the number of requests processed concurrently. This approach decouples the message ingestion rate from RabbitMQ and the internal processing throughput of the system, thereby improving stability under burst traffic conditions.
●	RabbitMQ Prefetch: Configured with a default value of 40. This ensures that each consumer retrieves at most 40 messages at a time, preventing overload and enabling controlled backpressure.
●	System Capacity Check: Before dispatching a request to Argo, the worker queries the Argo API to determine the number of currently running workflows. This allows the system to make admission control decisions based on real-time cluster capacity, avoiding excessive workload submission.
b. Lifecycle Management
●	Acknowledgement (Ack): Messages are acknowledged only after the corresponding Argo Workflow has successfully accepted the request. This guarantees at least once delivery semantics while preventing premature message removal.
●	Negative Acknowledgement (Nack): In the event of system failures or deserialization errors, messages are either discarded or re-queued depending on the failure type and retry policy. This ensures robustness in message handling and fault tolerance.
c. Message TTL Handling
The system implements a two-layer protection mechanism to eliminate stale or unmanaged deployment requests, thereby conserving cluster resources and maintaining operational efficiency.
●	Infrastructure Layer (RabbitMQ TTL):
 This serves as the first line of defense, automatically expiring messages at the queue level without requiring worker intervention. It prevents the accumulation of outdated requests in the messaging system.
●	Application Layer (Application-level TTL):
 This layer handles messages that may remain in intermediate states, such as those buffered in memory or delayed due to I/O operations. By enforcing TTL at the application level, the system ensures that no stale requests are processed even outside the queue boundary.
3.1.4 Infrastructure configuration
To ensure the stability of core cluster operations, the K3s server node shall be isolated from general application workloads.
•	Mechanism: Implementation of a NoSchedule taint on the control-plane node. Only essential system components (etcd, API server, Scheduler) with matching tolerations are permitted to be executed on this node.
•	Rationale: In a K3s environment where system-reserved configurations are limited, tainting serves as the primary defense against resource contention. This ensures the API server remains responsive, and the Scheduler retains sufficient CPU cycles to process placement decisions during burst traffic.
•	Effectiveness: Prevents cascading failures where a spike in challenge pods starves the Control Plane of resources, leading to cluster-wide unresponsiveness.
The system shall enforce explicit resource contracts and execution deadlines for all Argo Workflows.
•	Resource Requests/Limits: Every workflow pod must declare precise CPU and Memory requests. This enables the Scheduler to perform admission control based on actual node capacity rather than optimistic over-commitment.
•	Temporal Constraints (activeDeadlineSeconds): A global timeout is enforced at the workflow level. If a workflow fails to progress (e.g., due to schedulable challenge pods) within the defined window, the Argo Controller shall forcefully terminate the process.
•	Effectiveness: Transitions the system to a "fail-fast" model. Resources are automatically released from stalled workflows, preventing the accumulation of "Zombie" processes that previously paralyzed the Argo Controller.

3.1.5. Implementation Rationale: Resolving the IS-6 Resource Deadlock
The transition to an asynchronous admission-controlled model specifically addresses the architectural gaps in the legacy Argo-direct submission flow:
a. Resolution of Argo Controller Saturation and Observability Deficit
Problem: In the legacy design, 1,000 concurrent requests were submitted directly to the Argo Workflow Controller. This led to a "Controller Saturation" state where the system could not effectively track the status of individual requests. Argo’s internal queue became unmanageable, providing zero visibility into which requests were valid, stalled, or duplicated.
Resolution: By introducing RabbitMQ as a pre-submission buffer, the system gains full observability. Each request is tracked as a discrete message before it ever reaches Argo. This allows the DeploymentConsumer to act as a gatekeeper, ensuring only a manageable volume of work is "admitted" into Argo, keeping the Argo Controller's internal state clean and responsive.
b. Precision TTL and Stale Request Pruning
Problem: Argo Workflow lacks a high-precision TTL mechanism for requests in the "Pending" or "Submitted" stage under extreme load. Once a request was accepted by Argo, it became nearly impossible to programmatically expire it if the cluster was already hanging, leading to "Zombie Workflows" that occupied slots indefinitely.
Resolution: The new Two-Layer TTL strategy provides deterministic expiration.
•	Messages in the queue expire naturally via RabbitMQ TTL if not processed within the timeout window.
•	The Application-level TTL allows the Worker to discard requests that have become stale during the capacity-wait period. This ensures that only "fresh" requests are ever submitted to Argo, preventing the execution of irrelevant or outdated deployments.
c. Mitigation of Control Plane Deadlocks via Backpressure
Problem: Argo’s attempt to process a massive backlog of workflows placed an indirect, unthrottled load on the K3s and API server. Without a way to "pause" submissions at the application level, the entire Control Plane eventually deadlocked.
Resolution: The Admission Control (Step 17-18) creates an explicit backpressure loop. By querying the actual running workflow count before submission, the system prevents the "Submission Storm" that previously paralyzed the Argo Controller and the underlying K3s infrastructure.
