3.11. Improve File Access Control
The system shall enforce secure file access by implementing both infrastructure-level isolation and application-level authorization controls. This design aims to mitigate risks related to unauthorized file access, path traversal, and over-privileged storage exposure.
3.11.1 Infrastructure-Level Controls
a. Principle of Least Privilege
The system shall restrict access to the Network File System (NFS) by limiting each service to only the minimum required directories 
For example: 
The contestant-be service shall only mount: /srv/nfs/share/file
Access to other directories such as:
/srv/nfs/share/challenges
/srv/nfs/share/start-challenge
Is not granted access to this service.
This ensures that even if application-level controls are bypassed, unauthorized access to sensitive files (e.g., flags, internal resources) remains prevented.
The system shall enforce fine-grained access control using Access Control Lists (ACLs) based on service-specific user IDs.
Access Matrix:

/Challenges	/Start-challenge	/file
Admin-mvc
rwx		rwx
filebrowser	rwx	rwx	rwx
contestant-be
		r-x
up-challenge-workflow			r-x
start-challenge-workflow		r-x	

b. Root Squash Enforcement
The NFS server is configured with the root_squash option to map root users from client containers to a non-privileged anonymous user (UID 65534).
Access permissions for the anonymous user are explicitly defined using ACL to allow only the minimum required read access for specific directories.
This configuration ensures that services running as root inside containers do not gain elevated privileges on the NFS server and are restricted to non-privileged access.
c. Network Access Restriction
The NFS server is configured with IP-based export rules to restrict access to a predefined set of trusted cluster nodes.
Only the IP addresses of authorized nodes are allowed to mount the NFS share. All other network access is denied by default.
This configuration ensures that the NFS storage is only accessible from controlled infrastructure components and is not exposed to external or unauthorized internal systems.
3.11.2 Application-Level Controls
 
a. Token-Based Authentication and Authorization
All file access requests shall be authenticated using a secure token that contains identity and authorization metadata, including user_id, file_id, and team_id.
The backend shall validate the integrity of the token using a cryptographic signature and verify that the user_id embedded in the token matches the identity associated with the current user session.
This mechanism ensures that only authenticated users with valid tokens can initiate file access requests and prevents unauthorized or forged requests originating from the client side.
b. File-Level Authorization Binding
The system shall enforce strict binding between the requested file and the authorization data stored in the backend.
File access shall only be granted when the file_id extracted from the token exactly matches the corresponding file record in the database.
Any request with mismatched identifiers or attempts to manipulate file-related parameters shall be immediately rejected.
This mechanism eliminates the risk of Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR) by ensuring that file access decisions are based solely on trusted server-side data.
c. Controlled Path Resolution
The system shall treat all user-provided file path parameters as untrusted input.
Before accessing any file, the system shall:
Normalize the path using canonical path resolution
Validate that the resolved path remains within the designated NFS storage boundary
Any attempt to traverse directories, escape the allowed storage scope, or access unauthorized system files shall be rejected at the application layer.
This ensures that all file operations are confined strictly within approved storage directories.
d. Challenge-Based Access Control
For files associated with challenge content, the system shall enforce additional business logic constraints to control access based on competition state and user progress.
The system shall:
-	Verify that the associated challenge exists and is not in a hidden state
-	Validate that all prerequisite challenges have been completed
-	Confirm that the requesting user or team has the appropriate access rights
Requests that do not satisfy these conditions shall be denied.
This mechanism ensures controlled access to challenge resources and preserves the integrity and fairness of the competition environment.
